    "citation": "Spruill 2001 11714214",
    "population": "N: 40 (USA) Age: 43.4 (12-85) WT: ~73±~44",
    "model_type": "PK",
    "objective": "“we compared predicted phenytoin serum concentrations using three Michaelis-Menten pharmacokinetic dosing methods with actual concentrations obtained from physician dosing in an outpatient neurology practice”",
    "covariates": "Tested: - Included: -",
    "observations": "Population-based parameter values were used to calculate doses and compared to those calculated by physicians. In general, a Bayesian method that takes into account the previous information seems to perform more optimally. The impact of the time of sampling was not taken into account by applying time dependent kinetics, thereby possibly reducing the accuracy of the calculated dosing algorithm.",
    "dose": "Steady-state oral doses in patients",
    "structure": "Simplified PK",
    "equations": "Km=(dose1-dose2)/((dose1/conc1)-(dose2/conc2)) Vm=(dose2*(Km+conc2))/conc2 PD=(Vm*NTC)/(Km+NTC) The above requires 2 concentrations (conc1/2) being measured over 2 separate dosing events (dose1/2). Based on this algorithm, the predicted dose (PD) in mg/day to reach a normal therapeutic concentration (NTC, for example 15 mg/L) can be calculated.",
    "parameter_values": "-",
    "validation": "No/Yes (validated on 16 subjects)"
  },
